2. Network Segmentation and Traffic
On the diagram, clearly show:

VPC and Subnets

One VPC for production.

Public subnets (load balancer only).

Private subnets (app and data tiers).

Security Controls

Internet → WAF/Load Balancer (HTTPS only, TLS termination).

WAF/Load Balancer → App subnets (restricted ports only).

App subnets → DB and storage (internal, limited ports).

Management access (VPN or SSO + bastion) into admin/infra.

Use arrows to show allowed traffic flows, and annotate key firewall/security group rules (e.g., “HTTPS 443 only”, “App → DB 5432 only”).

3. Security Features to Label
Add small callouts or labels for:

TLS everywhere between clients, edge, and internal services.

Security groups / firewall rules protecting each zone.

MFA + SSO for admin access to cloud console, CI/CD, and production.

Central logging (app, infra) feeding into log/monitoring platform.

This lets auditors visually see how CC6 (logical access) and CC8 (operations) are implemented.

4. Minimal Legend / Text Companion
Create a one‑page “Network Architecture – Notes” with bullets:

Production is hosted in <cloud provider> within a dedicated VPC, segmented into public, application, and data subnets.

Only the load balancer/API gateway is internet‑facing; app and data tiers reside in private subnets, reachable only via controlled security groups.

Admin and DevOps access production via SSO/MFA and VPN (or bastion), not directly over the public internet.

